commit.message: Replace deprecated BadZipfile with BadZipFile

Support indent using interger format

Originally `unparse(pretty=True, indent=2)` would fail
with confusing error message,
as it only supported `unparse(pretty=True, indent='  ')`

This commit adds support for int indent

Without this, `python -m unittest tests/*.py` would complain
`ModuleNotFoundError: No module named 'tests.test_dicttoxml'`
Ensure significant whitespace is not trimmed
added conda installation command
Add test coverage for #278
fix attributes not appearing in streaming mode

Fix Travis CI status badge URL

Fixes #296

commit.message: Update push_release.sh to use twine.
Bump version and update CHANGELOG.

setup: open README.md with a specific encoding

With python3, the built-in open() function opens files in "text" mode by
default (i.e. the f.read() method reads bytes and tries to decode them
to unicode using the interpreter default encoding). Depending on the
system locale, this default encoding may be 'ascii'. Which leads to the
following error:

 ~$ python3 setup.py egg_info
 Traceback (most recent call last):
   File "setup.py", line 12, in <module>
     long_description = f.read()
   File "/usr/lib/python3.6/encodings/ascii.py", line 26, in decode
     return codecs.ascii_decode(input, self.errors)[0]
 UnicodeDecodeError: 'ascii' codec can't decode byte 0xc3 in position
 2587: ordinal not in range(128)

The character at position 2587 is 'ô' (from Fantômas) and is utf-8
encoded.

Force to open the file in "binary" mode (which is the only mode on
python2) and explicitly decode the read bytes to unicode using the
'utf-8' codec.

Fixes: 8374e7d84f92 ("Use Markdown long_description on PyPI (#190)")
